“All the songs sound different.

They don’t know who they want to be.”

- matty healy for the guardian (2016)

Before their manager, Jamie Oborne, created Dirty Hit records and signed them himself, Manchester four-piece the 1975 couldn’t get signed to a label.

The problem was attributed to the band’s lack of genre consistency.

“That’s your problem,

they told the music industry in response:

You don’t understand the way

people listen to music these days.”

- simon hattenstone for the guardian (2016)

The 1975 moved forward with their jukebox-like sound, and three No. 1 albums, numerous awards, and a Reading and Leeds headlining spot later, it seems their bet has paid off.

Here’s a journey through the 1975’s discography, in an attempt to make sense of the “polarizing nature” of the band’s songs in a way magazine reviewers haven’t: with data.

A Textual and Aural Analysis of

The 1975

This piece is organized in four parts, each representing a musical era of the 1975. Each part will provide some background, and then break down the top three most popular songs from that era, textually and aurally.

Part I. The EPs

Before their debut album, the 1975 released four EPs throughout 2012 and 2013. This was when they first earned broader attention, particulary when they began to receive regular spin on BBC Radio. Huw Stephens was the first to play one of their tracks (the EP version of “The City”) live on air.

Based on Spotify play counts, their most popular songs from the EPs that were not eventually re-recorded for the debut are “Fallingforyou,” “Me,” and “You.”

Let’s aurally analyze those tracks. Spotify’s API provides audio features in numerical format.

Their two most popular songs from this era, “Fallingforyou” and “Me,” are defined by low danceability, energy, and valence. The third most popular track, “You,” separates from that pattern, specifically when it comes to valence. In fact, “You” often breaks from the pattern of the other two tracks: while all three vary in tempo, “You” has low acousticness and high speechiness.

Part II. The Self-Titled Debut

In September 2013, the 1975 released their self-titled debut album. The band started that year playing bars across the UK and were ending it with their first No. 1 on the UK Charts. Some tracks from the album also appeared on their EPs, but they were classified as part of the first album cycle in this analysis.

Their three most popular songs from this era are “Chocolate,” “Girls,” and “Robbers.”

All three of these tracks have much higher danceability and energy than the last three tracks.

Part III. I like it when you sleep, for you are so beautiful yet so unaware of it

After massive, mind-boggling success in an abnormally short amount of time, the 1975, who at first appeared to be at their breaking point, went away to create an even more successful album than their first. In 2016, I like it when you sleep, for you are so beautiful yet so unaware of it not only debuted at No. 1 on the UK charts—but also on the US charts as well.

Their three most popular songs from this era are “Somebody Else,” “The Sound,” and “UGH!”

Part IV. A Brief Inquiry into Online Relationships

The massive album cycle for I like it when you sleep included iconic moments like a performance slot on Saturday Night Live, the Brit Award for Best British Band, and a sold-out headlining show at Madison Square Garden. In other words, going into their third album, A Brief Inquiry into Online Relationships, there was no stopping the 1975.

The next “era” of the 1975 is actually titled Music For Cars (fittingly, also the name of their third EP) and contains two albums as a follow-up to I like it when you sleep. The first, A Brief Inquiry, released in November 2018, and the forthcoming Notes on a Conditional Form is coming in the middle of 2019.

With that explained, let’s dive in to the three most popular songs from A Brief Inquiry: “TOOTIMETOOTIMETOOTIME,” “Love It If We Made It,” and “Give Yourself a Try.”

Part V. Conclusion

There is a pattern of repetition in the lyrics of the 1975’s most popular songs, as seen in the top 20 trigrams from each album. While we are able to pull an interesting lyrical pattern from the popular end of their catalogue, the audio features derived are much more scattered. In general, the albums have high energy in their most popular songs and, with a couple exceptions, high danceability as well. However, the other features are less clear.

Chronology has yielded even less pattern than popularity, with none of the audio features showing any type of correlation.

Always defined by ashape-shifting approach when it comes to genre, the 1975 show little consistency in the data underlying their songs. While small patterns can be derived from individual album eras, no distint pattern in audio features emerged when using data scraped from Spotify for each song, particularly the most popular. Through trigram analysis on their tracks, we can theorize that their most popular tracks from each release display a sense of repetativeness.

However, with this data-driven analysis, we can conclude that the 1975 live up to their genre-less style that they perform so well.
